half_total = run_df[run_df['Event'] == 'Half marathon']
top100 = half_total.head(100)

df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Total': half_total['Season'].value_counts(),
    'Top100': top100['Season'].value_counts()
}).fillna(0)

df['Total_prop'] = df['Total'] / df['Total'].sum()
df['Top100_prop'] = df['Top100'] / df['Top100'].sum()

melted = df[['Total_prop', 'Top100_prop']].reset_index().melt(id_vars='Season', var_name='Type', value_name='Proportion')
melted['Type'] = melted['Type'].replace({'Total_prop': 'Total', 'Top100_prop': 'Top 100'})

sns.barplot(data=melted, x='Season', y='Proportion', hue='Type')
plt.title('Top 100 vs Total — Half marathon')
plt.show()

Autumn clearly offers the best conditions for elite half marathon times, likely due to cooler weather and a dense race calendar.We can see an overperformance.¶

Summer underperforms despite high participation, probably due to heat stress.¶

Spring remains stable, while winter suffers from harsher conditions.¶

Tenkm=run_df[run_df['Event']=='10,000 m']
top100=Tenkm.head(100)
df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Total': Tenkm['Season'].value_counts(),
    'Top100': top100['Season'].value_counts()
}).fillna(0)

df['Total_prop'] = df['Total'] / df['Total'].sum()
df['Top100_prop'] = df['Top100'] / df['Top100'].sum()

melted = df[['Total_prop', 'Top100_prop']].reset_index().melt(id_vars='Season', var_name='Type', value_name='Proportion')
melted['Type'] = melted['Type'].replace({'Total_prop': 'Total', 'Top100_prop': 'Top 100'})

sns.barplot(data=melted, x='Season', y='Proportion', hue='Type')
plt.title('Top 100 vs Total — 10,000 m')
plt.show()

Unlike the half marathon, summer dominates both participation and Top 100 results in the 10,000 m. This likely reflects a busy summer race calendar and the fact that heat impacts semi-short distances less. Winter is almost absent due to fewer races and tough weather.¶

To sum up:¶

Autumn clearly boosts performances in long distances like the half marathon.¶

Summer, on the other hand, enhances sprint performance, but shows weaker results on longer runs.¶

After analyzing the data, we can say that season and by extension, weather does have an impact on running performance, depending on the type of event. However, we should be cautious: since competitions are not evenly spread throughout the year, our results may reflect participation trends more than pure physical performance.¶

df_women = run_df[run_df['Gender'] == 'Women']
count_women = df_women['Year'].value_counts()
valid_years_women = count_women[count_women > 10].index
df_women = df_women[df_women['Year'].isin(valid_years_women)]

finalwomen_df = df_women.groupby(['Event', 'Year'])['Time_seconds'].mean().reset_index()

sns.FacetGrid(finalwomen_df, col='Event', col_wrap=3, height=4, sharey=False).map(sns.lineplot, 'Year', 'Time_seconds')
plt.suptitle("Average Time per Event per Year (Women)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Conclusion by event and year¶

Female performances show a general improvement across all events, especially in sprint and middle-distance races. While some yearly variations exist, the overall trend reflects a steady performance increase, highlighting the rise of women’s athletics.¶

3.The Impact of Age on Athletic Performance¶

run_df['Date'] = pd.to_datetime(run_df['Date'])
run_df['Date of Birth'] = pd.to_datetime(run_df['Date of Birth'])
run_df['Age'] = (run_df['Date'] -run_df['Date of Birth']).dt.days // 365

df_grouped = run_df.groupby(['Event', 'Age'])['Time_seconds'].mean().reset_index()
graph=sns.FacetGrid(df_grouped, col='Event', col_wrap=3, height=4, sharey=False).map_dataframe(sns.lineplot, x='Age', y='Time_seconds')
graph.set(xlim=(15,40))
plt.suptitle("Average time per ages and event", fontsize=16)
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.90)

Overall, these graphs reveal a clear trend: a decline in speed is associated with increasing age.¶

top100 = ( run_df.sort_values(by='Time_seconds').groupby('Event').head(100))
sns.FacetGrid(top100, col="Event", col_wrap=3, height=4, sharex=False, sharey=False).map(sns.histplot, "Age", kde=True, bins=10, color="mediumseagreen").fig.suptitle("Age distribution in the Top 100 performances (by event)", fontsize=14)
plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.90)
plt.show()

Overall, we observe the same trends across all our graphs, with a strong dominance of the 21–25 age group among the top 100 times in each event¶

top10 = run_df.sort_values(by='Time_seconds').groupby('Event').head(10)
median_age_top10 = top10.groupby('Event')['Age'].median().reset_index(name='Age_top10')

top1 = run_df.sort_values(by='Time_seconds').groupby('Event').head(1)
record_age = top1[['Event', 'Age']].rename(columns={'Age': 'Age_record'})

df_lollipop = record_age.merge(median_age_top10, on='Event')

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for i, row in df_lollipop.iterrows():
    plt.plot([i, i], [row['Age_record'], row['Age_top10']], color='gray', lw=2)
    plt.scatter(i, row['Age_record'], color='red', s=80, label='Âge du record' if i == 0 else "")
    plt.scatter(i, row['Age_top10'], color='green', s=80, label='Âge médian top 10' if i == 0 else "")
plt.xticks(range(len(df_lollipop)), df_lollipop['Event'], rotation=45)
plt.ylabel("Âge")
plt.title("Record age's vs Top10 median ages ", fontsize=14)    
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

The lollipop chart clearly shows that younger athletes (mostly between 22 and 25 years old) dominate the majority of events, especially in sprints and middle-distance races.However, in longer-distance events such as the half-marathon and marathon, this trend shifts.Older athletes remain highly competitive, sometimes even holding the best performances.¶

Conclusion¶

While age clearly shapes athletic performance, its impact varies by event type.In sprints and middle distances, athletes typically peak between 22 and 25, when speed and power are at their maximum.¶

However, in long-distance events like the half-marathon and marathon, older athletes remain highly competitive.¶

This reflects real-world dynamics: while speed declines with age, endurance and efficiency can improve over time, supported by years of training and race experience.¶
